[1]
Date: Wed 23 Aug 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Radio Netherlands, 22 Aug 2006 [edited]
<http://www.radionetherlands.nl/currentaffairs/ned060822>

EU acts to contain bluetongue outbreak
---------------------------------------------
Europe has introduced measures to halt the spread of the bluetongue virus,
which can be fatal to sheep. In the Netherlands, Luxembourg and large areas
of Belgium and Germany, an export ban is now in place for cows, sheep and
goats, so the Netherlands is no longer the only country with a stringent
policy on bluetongue. It should be emphasized that bluetongue is not
dangerous to humans.
On Monday [21 Aug 2006], European agricultural experts imposed a ban on the
transport of cows, sheep and goats within a radius of 20 km around farms
where bluetongue has been diagnosed. In other words, the animals are not
allowed to leave the farms. The export ban is in effect over a radius of
150 km around the infected farms. In this area, animals can be taken to
slaughterhouses under strict security regulations, but may not be exported
abroad.
The export ban will initially apply for one week. This is to give experts
the opportunity to resolve a number of questions surrounding the outbreak
of bluetongue. For example, it's still not clear which variant of the virus
is involved, which makes it impossible to find a suitable vaccine. They
also want to know how a disease previously only known in southern Europe
managed to reach northwest Europe in the 1st place.
What is known at present is that a family of small mosquito-like flies,
known as biting midges or no-see-ums, transmit the virus by sucking blood
from an infected animal and biting a healthy one.
Stringent measures are needed now that the virus has spread to the
countries surrounding the Netherlands, with bluetongue now having been
diagnosed on farms in Belgium and Germany.
These measures are nothing new in the Netherlands. Late last week, as soon
as the disease was identified, Dutch Agriculture Minister Cees Veerman
imposed a nationwide export ban for sheep, goats and cows. He emphasized
how important it was that other countries should not lose confidence in the
quality of Dutch livestock.
Neighboring countries did not adopt the same policy, although the 1st
incidence of bluetongue was at a sheep farm in the far south of the
Netherlands in Kerkrade, near the border with Belgium and Germany. This
meant that sheep, cows and goats were allowed into the Netherlands from
Belgium and Germany but not in the opposite direction, despite the fact
that the chance of infection in those countries was just as great.
The Dutch farmers' and growers' organization LTO was disappointed by these
measures and pointed out that farmers would lose a great deal of money if
they were unable to the export their livestock. The LTO estimates that the
ban on exporting cattle alone represents losses of 5 million euros [USD 6.4
million] a week. Once again, the organization complained, the Netherlands
was falling over itself to make a good impression in Europe. A number of
politicians also thought Mr. Veerman had gone too far.
Now that other EU member states have also taken steps against bluetongue,
Minister Veerman looks to have been vindicated. But not everyone agrees.
The livestock exporting firm Nammen Schaap comments:
"It indicates that the minister was initially too strict with the sector.
In a way, he has been reined in a little. We know now that we'll have to
take it easy for a week, but there's a real chance that in a week's time,
exports can get back to normal again."
In any case, the nationwide export ban doesn't seem to have been such a bad
idea, now that more possible cases have been reported in Woerden and Sneek,
in the center and north of the Netherlands [see item 3 further].
Minister Veerman can understand the farmers' frustration, but stands by his
policy:
"I understand it's disappointing for some people, but on the other hand, we
know you can't be cautious enough when it comes to animal diseases. We're
talking about 4 days now that exports have been halted. Let's hope the
reports from Sneek and Woerden are false alarms. And don't forget, the
European Commission has given us discretion to lift the export ban in the
course of the week."
For now, Dutch farmers will just have to pray that cold weather comes as
soon as possible. That will kill the midges and mean the disease will have
been defeated in a purely natural way, for the time being.
[Byline: Arwen Grafhorst]
--
