Date: Wed 23 Aug 2006
From: Maria Zampaglione <m.zampaglione@oie.inttel>
Source: OIE press release, 23 Aug 2006 [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/press/en_060823.htm>

Bluetongue detected for the 1st time in Northern Europe
-----------------------------------------------
Dutch, Belgian and German Authorities have officially notified the World
Organisation for Animal Health (OIE) of the occurrence of an outbreak of
bluetongue in sheep on their territory. The notification reports are
available on the OIE website:
<http://www.oie.int>.
According to the 1st report sent by the Dutch on 18 Aug 2006, the outbreak
affected a farm in the province of Limburg. Bluetongue was confirmed by
laboratory investigations. The source of the infection is currently under
investigation.
Intensive surveillance activities conducted by Dutch as well as Belgian and
German authorities revealed additional affected farms in proximity to the
index case.
Dutch, as well as Belgian and German authorities have taken classical
disease control measures, such as zoning and movement control and
continuous surveillance within the country. Further screening will be
continued to determine the extent of the outbreaks.
Bluetongue is an insect-borne viral disease to which all species of
ruminants are susceptible. The disease poses no danger to human health. It
was 1st described in South Africa, where it has probably been endemic in
wild ruminants from antiquity, but has since been recognized in most
countries in the tropics and sub-tropics. The global distribution of the
disease comprising the endemic areas of bluetongue has traditionally been
accepted to be between the latitudes of approximately 50oN and 35oS. [see
comment]. Aside from the endemic areas, since 1999, there have been reports
of outbreaks of bluetongue in Greece, Italy, France (Corsica) and Spain
(Balearic Islands). Cases also occurred in Europe in Bulgaria, Croatia,
Macedonia, Kosova and Yugoslavia (see OIE website).
Bluetongue occurs mostly during periods of high temperature and rainfall
and usually disappears with the 1st frost or severe cold weather.
The 1st occurrence of the disease in the Netherlands signifies the most
northern locality where the disease has ever been diagnosed.
An emerging disease is defined as a new infection resulting from the
evolution or change of an existing pathogen or parasite resulting in a
change of host range, vector, pathogenicity or strain. Occurring for the
1st time in the northern part of the European hemisphere, bluetongue may be
considered as an emerging disease in this area.
Globalization, the change in weather patterns, and the increase in speed
and volume of international transport, as well as passenger travel, are
known factors that could favor the spread of pathogens and the emergence of
disease.
The rapid detection and response as well as the excellent collaboration
demonstrated by the veterinary authorities in the Netherlands, Germany and
Belgium during this emerging disease have been crucial for the containment
of spread and the development of all disease control measures.
Although the source of infection of this outbreak is still under
investigation, the OIE highlights the importance of having effective
veterinary services. The ability to detect early and respond rapidly to an
unexpected event such as this is dependent upon the effectiveness of a
national surveillance system and transparency in reporting. Veterinary
services are guarantors of animal health and, by association with zoonotic
diseases, public health.
--
Maria Zampaglione
Communication Department, OIE
<m.zampaglione@oie.int>
[Until 1998, BTV strains have been identified in many tropical and
temperate areas of the world from a latitude of approximately 40oN (or,
according to some investigators, 42oN) to 35oS. The disease has since
spread northwards, the most northerly affected location (to the best
knowledge of this moderator), prior to the current incursion into the
Netherlands being reported by Yugoslavia in the region of Sebac (44o43'N)
in September 2002.
There is, however, one exception: occasional incursions of bluetongue have
occurred in the Okanagan Valley of British Columbia, Canada, since 1976.
The last official identification of BTV there was notified to the OIE in
October-November 1998, when BTV11 was isolated from 2 bovines out of a
sentinel herd of 7. Previously, incursions were detected in the same
location in late August 1987 and in September 1988. The site is situated 16
km north of 49oN (which is the border with the USA; see map at
<http://www.winesnw.com/images/BC_MainOkanaganMap.gif>).
The Okanagan Valley has been defined as a separate zone within Canada so
that the rest of Canada can maintain bluetongue-free status according to
international standards. - Mod.AS]
