Date: Wed 23 Aug 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Letter of the Dutch Minister of Agriculture, Nature and Food
Safety, Dr. C.P. Veerman, to the parliament, 22 Aug 2006 [excerpts,
translated from Dutch, edited]
<http://www9.minlnv.nl/servlet/page?_pageid=106&_dad=portal30&_schema=PORTAL30&p_item_id=129707>

This is an update of the bluetongue situation further to a previous letter
of 18 Aug 2006.
Up to this moment [Tue 22 Aug 2006], bluetongue has been confirmed on
almost 20 Dutch farms. These include sheep as well as cattle farms, all
within the 20-km zone established on 18 Aug 2006 in south Netherlands.
In addition, there are several [other] suspected farms where, momentarily,
investigations are being carried out by the Food and Consumer Product
Safety Authority (VWA). This relates, in addition to farms in south
Netherlands, also to one sheep farm in the vicinity of Sneek and suspected
cattle on a [pre-export] collecting enterprise [farm] in Woerden. The
initial lab results of samples from the sheep farm in Sneek, tested by CIDC
[Central Institute for Animal Disease Control], Lelystad, are not
unambiguous; new samples will be tested by CIDC as well as by the European
reference laboratory at Pirbright (UK). No results are yet available from
the cattle in Woerden.
Tracing-back investigations have revealed that previous contacts might have
taken place between the Woerden farm and the infected area in south
Netherlands. There are no indications on such contacts relating to the
suspected sheep farm in Sneek. Final lab results from both farms are
expected within a few days.
In my previous letter, I have explained to have banned exports in wait for
the results of the investigations into possible spread of the virus into
other parts of the Netherlands. The fact that there are suspected cases in
northern areas underlines the importance of the said steps. The European
Commission as well has regarded this measure as reasonable.
In view of the consequences of this measure for the exporting sector, great
efforts are being made to obtain the information which might enable
reconsidering the export ban as early as possible. In case further spread
to the north is not confirmed and no extension of the infected zone is
observed, the export ban will be terminated at the earliest. Such a
decision is also dependent upon the results of the rapid surveillance
activities ("quickscan") for the presence of the virus in sheep and cattle,
undertaken in northern territories, and the tracing-back investigations.
The decision on the matter might be expected before the end this week.
Alongside the tracing-back investigations and the contemplated rapid
virological surveillance ("quickscan"), efforts are invested in the
performance of the obligatory, extensive epidemiological survey. This
includes studies into the distribution of the BT vectors (_Culicoides_
species) in the Netherlands and the rate of their infection. The survey is
carried out by our own investigators assisted by bluetongue experts from Italy.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[For the location of Woerden, in the province Utrecht, see map at
<http://www.multimap.com/map/browse.cgi?lat=52.0861&lon=4.8839&scale=500000&icon=x>
For the location of Sneek, in the province Friesland, see map at
<http://www.multimap.com/map/browse.cgi?lat=53.0337&lon=5.6606&scale=200000&icon=x>.
The Dutch decision to voluntarily suspend all exports of ruminants upon the
initial diagnosis of bluetongue, in wait for final diagnosis --
particularly subtyping -- and for the results of the rapidly implemented
epidemiological surveillance to evaluate the route and extent of
transmission, deserves to be highly praised. It is helpful in preventing
possible spread to target markets, enables the timely application of
additional precautionary measures and safeguards the future and good name
of exported Dutch livestock and products.
Today, 23 Aug 2006, the permission to export ruminant sperma, ovi and
embryos from the BT-affected areas in the Netherlands has been renewed by
the ministry, provided they had been derived prior to 1 May 2006.
Results of the initiated Dutch surveillance, and the outcome of pending
laboratory investigations -- mainly in the reference laboratory, and
particularly regarding the serotyping of the causal agent -- are urgently
anticipated. - Mod.AS]
